stylometry: @RISK is a program that takes the 5 inputs of a simulation and runs 1000 iterations. Iterations are basically what would happen for that data set when run with 1000 different data points. The mean, standard deviation, maxes, mins, etc. are all taken and that is what @RISK shows when you run a simulation. The data is analyzed according to the probability distribution you have @RISK set up to use. If the data is set to be normal it will run the simulation as such, meaning it will stardardize the data for you. If you use a triangular distribution then it will run the simulation to "fit" the triangular distrubution.
